The error occurred because you have existing items in your database with lowercase or mixed-case part numbers. The database cannot enforce a "Must be Uppercase" rule until the existing data is fixed.

### 🚨 Corrected SQL Command
Run this **exact** script in your Supabase SQL Editor. It fixes the existing data first, then sets up the permissions and the rule:

```sql
-- 1. Fix existing data: Convert all part numbers to UPPERCASE
UPDATE inventory SET part_number = UPPER(part_number);

-- 2. Setup/Reset RLS Policies (Allows the app to change stock levels)
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Allow public update" ON inventory;
CREATE POLICY "Allow public update" ON inventory FOR UPDATE USING (true) WITH CHECK (true);

DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Allow public select" ON inventory;
CREATE POLICY "Allow public select" ON inventory FOR SELECT USING (true);

DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Allow public insert" ON inventory;
CREATE POLICY "Allow public insert" ON inventory FOR INSERT WITH CHECK (true);

-- 3. Now add the constraint: Ensure future entries are always UPPERCASE
ALTER TABLE inventory DROP CONSTRAINT IF EXISTS part_number_case_check;
ALTER TABLE inventory ADD CONSTRAINT part_number_case_check CHECK (part_number = UPPER(part_number));
```

### Application Updates
I have updated the `transactionService.ts` to be much more strict. It will now **throw errors** if a stock update fails, ensuring you see exactly what went wrong in the UI instead of a silent failure.

